uthors show why "the method question" has moved to the top of many feminist research and interpretive research strategies, and engage in thinking about how ideas and actions have developed within complex social circumstances. The essays in this book challenge the tradition that has allowed abstracted, formalized versions of the ideas and experiences of privileged white men to set standards for how everyone should conduct themselves. The authors use new-found knowledge to displace the dominant ideology constructed around race, class, gender, and heterosexual privilege, and then propose innovative feminist-informed analyses of subjects as diverse as political change, critical linguistics, child care, religious studies, and violence against women.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 4aCoursebook. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Feminism & Feminist Theory.2bisacsh1 aArchibald, Linda, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBurt, Sandra, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBurt, Sandra, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aChampagne, Cheryl, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCode, Lorraine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCode, Lorraine, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aColwell, Kristin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCrnkovich, Mary, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEhrlich, Susan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGreaves, Lorraine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHall, M. Ann, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKarch, Louise, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relator